Two Pointer / Sliding Window

Constant Window Concept : When problem is given to find maximum sum, minimum sum in a given array, we use constant window concept.

Fixed-Size Sliding Window:
The size of the window (\(K\)) remains constant throughout the execution. You shift the window one element at a time.

Example: Find the maximum sum of any contiguous subarray of size \(K\).
Mechanism:
  Compute the value of the first window (indices 0 to K-1).
  Slide the window right by 1 index.
  Update the value: New Sum = Previous Sum - Outgoing Element + Incoming Element.

##Sample Code

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
       int arr[]={1,2,3,2,1,1,2,1};
       int k=4;
       System.out.println(MaxiSum(arr,k));
    }
    public static int MaxiSum(int arr[], int k){
        int l=0;
        int r=k-1;
        int maxSum=0,sum=0;
        
        for(int i=l;i<=r;i++){
            sum+=arr[i];
        }
        
        while(r<arr.length-1){
            sum=sum-arr[l];
            l++;
            r++;
            sum=sum+arr[r];
            maxSum=Math.max(maxSum,sum);
        }
        return maxSum;
    }

===> Finding Longest subarray or substring as per the given condition on question

Brute-Force Approach:-
Using two for loop for generating each subarray for sum value k
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
       int arr[]={2,5,1,7,10};
       int k=14;
       System.out.println(MaxLengthSubarray(arr,k));
    }
    public static int MaxLengthSubarray(int arr[], int k){
       int n=arr.length-1;
       int maxLen=0;
       for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
           int sum=0;
           for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
               sum=sum+arr[j];
               if(sum <= k){
                   maxLen=Math.max(maxLen,j-i+1);
               }
           }
       }
       return maxLen;
    }
}
}
